WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:12.920
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today,&nbsp;
we're going to look at the prettiest&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:21.240
theorem in calculus, which is a theorem&nbsp;
about cubic curves or cubic polynomials.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:25.040
This is one of a series of foundational&nbsp;
lectures in mathematics where I'm trying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:29.800
to establish proper logical foundations&nbsp;
for the subject. In the last few videos,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.800 --> 00:00:35.120
we've been talking about calculus in a&nbsp;
very elementary setting—the setting of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:41.040
polynomials. It turns out that we can do&nbsp;
calculus this way purely algebraically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:46.120
without any notions of limits, without any&nbsp;
notions of real numbers, and with complete&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.120 --> 00:00:54.840
precision of thought. We're now going to reap&nbsp;
the rewards by studying this beautiful theorem.

00:00:54.840 --> 00:01:05.760
So, cubics or cubic polynomials are something like&nbsp;
this: as a poly number, it's just a list of four&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:11.200
numbers. The four numbers are the coefficients&nbsp;
of the polynomial when it's written this way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:19.320
in standard alpha form. So, this polynomial&nbsp;
is of degree three if this coefficient, d,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:25.600
is not equal to zero, and we'll assume that from&nbsp;
now on. Then it's called a cubic polynomial. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:32.320
when we graph such a polynomial, in other words,&nbsp;
what we do is we plug in points of the form, say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:41.360
x-coordinate r and y-coordinate P(r), where P(r)&nbsp;
is what you get when you replace alpha here with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:47.000
the number r. If you plot all those points, then&nbsp;
you get a curve that looks something like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:54.720
perhaps sort of like this, or maybe going&nbsp;
up and down like this, or maybe like this.

00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:58.960
So now, the study of these cubic polynomials&nbsp;
and their graphs—essentially, we're talking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:07.240
about what are usually called functions of this&nbsp;
kind—is part of a larger study of cubic curves,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:14.320
where we consider a more general kind&nbsp;
of equations involving, say, x and y,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:22.520
polynomial equations where the total degree&nbsp;
is three. These cubic curves were studied by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:30.920
Descartes, by Newton—they were of interest to&nbsp;
almost all classical mathematicians because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.920 --> 00:02:37.120
there's a lot of really interesting things that&nbsp;
turn out to happen for cubic curves. Today,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:41.600
we're going to talk about a very special kind&nbsp;
of cubic curve—these cubic polynomials. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:45.680
it's important to realize that there's&nbsp;
a much bigger, more general theory,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.680 --> 00:02:50.000
of which what I'm going to say&nbsp;
to you now is only a small part.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:56.560
So, our strategy is to review calculus in this&nbsp;
elementary setting, in the context of cubic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.560 --> 00:03:01.720
polynomials, so you'll see exactly the steps&nbsp;
that we need to go through to establish the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:08.240
foundations of calculus for cubic polynomials,&nbsp;
and then we'll be able to state and prove this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:16.280
most pretty theorem. In fact, we'll be able&nbsp;
to do that all on one page. So, our strategy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:16.280 --> 00:03:25.520
is to first of all establish some of the basic&nbsp;
calculus constructions for cubic polynomials.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:31.680
We're going to start with the general cubic&nbsp;
polynomial a + b alpha + c alpha^2 + d alpha^3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:38.480
and we're going to compute various things for it.&nbsp;
We're going to compute the Taylor polynomial, or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:44.800
Taylor by polynomial; we're going to compute the&nbsp;
derivative and various higher sub-derivatives, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:52.520
then we're going to find the tangent polynomials&nbsp;
or tangent poly numbers for this thing.

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:57.560
Geometrically, that means we're going to be&nbsp;
studying a curve something like this. Perhaps this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:07.880
is the particular polynomial 5 - 3x - 4x^2 + x^3,&nbsp;
and then, say, at the point r = 1, the tangent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:13.480
line ends up looking something like this, and&nbsp;
the tangent conic is a parabola looking something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:20.120
like this. So, we want to be able to compute for&nbsp;
every value of r what the tangent line looks like,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.120 --> 00:04:29.160
what the tangent conic looks like, and our theorem&nbsp;
is going to be something about the tangent conics.

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:35.440
Alright, so the first order of business is to find&nbsp;
the Taylor polynomial for P. That, by definition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:46.160
is just P(alpha + beta). We replace the alphas&nbsp;
with alpha + beta, and then we expand that using&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:53.800
the binomial theorem here and here, and then&nbsp;
we collect terms—the terms not involving beta,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:59.640
the terms involving beta, the terms involving beta&nbsp;
squared, and the term just involving beta cubed.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:09.880
So, it's just a question of expanding these&nbsp;
binomial things out and putting it all together.

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:14.720
Now, these three coefficients that are appearing&nbsp;
here—actually, there's four of them including that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:21.600
one—these are the first sub-derivatives&nbsp;
of the polynomial we started with. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:29.880
this thing here is D0 of P, this one&nbsp;
is D1 of P or the derivative of P,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:38.440
this thing is D2 of P, and this constant D is D3&nbsp;
of P. D1 of P is just the same as the derivative,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:43.560
so this is the derivative of that. That's&nbsp;
how we define what the derivative is—the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:50.280
derivative is the coefficient of beta in&nbsp;
the Taylor polynomial. But at the same time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.280 --> 00:05:54.640
we also define the second sub-derivative,&nbsp;
the third sub-derivative, and, in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:59.640
the zero sub-derivative, which of course&nbsp;
is just the same as the polynomial itself.

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:05.680
So, just for good reference, let's write&nbsp;
down these various sub-derivatives that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:13.000
computed. The zeroth one was the polynomial&nbsp;
itself; there's the first sub-derivative,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.760
or just the derivative; there's the second&nbsp;
sub-derivative; and there's the third&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.760 --> 00:06:22.680
sub-derivative. Now, for those of you who are not&nbsp;
used to sub-derivatives and just think in terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:28.560
of derivatives, what is the second sub-derivative&nbsp;
in ordinary language? It's the derivative of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:34.640
derivative divided by two. So, if you take the&nbsp;
ordinary derivative of this and divide by two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:41.280
you get the second sub-derivative. And what's the&nbsp;
third sub-derivative? It's the derivative of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:41.280 --> 00:06:47.240
second sub-derivative divided by three. Take the&nbsp;
derivative of this, divide by three, and you get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.240 --> 00:06:52.360
the third sub-derivative. So, if you just want&nbsp;
to use differentiation, that's how you can go&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.360 --> 00:07:02.840
from one to the next—that's a simplified way of&nbsp;
thinking about what the various derivatives are.

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:07.760
Alright, now let's look at the Taylor expansion&nbsp;
at r. Now, this is obtained by doing two things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:14.160
to the previous expression. The first is&nbsp;
to interchange the roles of alpha and beta,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:17.800
so instead of expanding in powers&nbsp;
of beta, we're now expanding in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:24.000
powers of alpha. We started with P(alpha +&nbsp;
beta)—that's symmetrical in alpha and beta,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.960
so it's completely the same if we interchange&nbsp;
the alphas and betas. And then the second thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.960 --> 00:07:33.360
that we do is that the betas, which are&nbsp;
now appearing in each one of these things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:43.880
are replaced with a number r. So, we get that&nbsp;
expression: that's D0 of P evaluated at r,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:54.600
here's D1 of P evaluated at r, here's D2 of&nbsp;
P evaluated at r, and D3 of P evaluated at r.

00:07:54.600 --> 00:08:04.400
Now we make a shift or a translation in this&nbsp;
formula. We now replace alpha with alpha - r. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:08.840
translate, then the left-hand side&nbsp;
becomes just P(alpha)—in other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:14.720
the original polynomial—and then the alphas,&nbsp;
which are appearing here, here, and here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:22.840
are replaced by alpha - r—there, there, and&nbsp;
there. And this is called a Taylor expansion&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:28.920
of the polynomial P at r because it depends&nbsp;
on the number r that we've chosen. There's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:36.520
a different such expansion for every r,&nbsp;
and this is a fundamental object because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:44.400
it's from this that we read off the&nbsp;
various tangents to the polynomial.

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:53.120
The first, well, the zero tangent, is just the&nbsp;
value of the polynomial at r. If you set alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:53.120 --> 00:09:00.200
equal to r, then these terms all disappear, and&nbsp;
you're just left with that. The first tangent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:08.400
is the sum of the first terms all the way up to&nbsp;
degree 1. The second tangent is the sum of all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:14.240
the terms up to degree 2. The third tangent&nbsp;
is the sum of all the terms up to degree 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:19.720
which in this case is all of it. That's&nbsp;
the general pattern of how we write down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.720 --> 00:09:27.640
the tangents to the polynomial at&nbsp;
r—we just take initial parts of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:33.520
the Taylor expansion. In other words, we&nbsp;
truncate the Taylor expansion suitably.

00:09:33.520 --> 00:09:38.200
So, let's have a look at what the tangent&nbsp;
line and the tangent conic simplify to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:45.160
when we look at them carefully. So, here are&nbsp;
the first two terms in the Taylor expansion,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:45.160 --> 00:09:52.880
the degree 1 part of it. What we want to do now is&nbsp;
rewrite it. In other words, we want to expand it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:59.760
out and separate it into the things involving&nbsp;
alpha and the things not involving alpha. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:04.520
here are the things not involving alpha to begin&nbsp;
with, and then we're going to have to add to that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:10.080
minus r times each of these. And have a look at&nbsp;
what happens when we take minus r times each of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:17.160
these: minus r times b will exactly cancel with&nbsp;
this br that's already there. So, we'll have an a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:17.160 --> 00:10:25.920
but we will have no brs left. Here, there are&nbsp;
cr^2, and we're going to add to that -2cr for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:25.920 --> 00:10:40.400
a total of -cr^2. Here we have dr^3, and we're&nbsp;
adding to that -3dr^3 for a total of -2dr^3. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:49.440
coefficient of alpha is just this, so it's just&nbsp;
copied unchanged. That is the tangent line to P&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:59.720
at r, and here's our symbol for it: it's the&nbsp;
first tangent, the first tangent to P at r.

00:10:59.720 --> 00:11:07.080
Okay, now we're going to look at the second&nbsp;
tangent to P at r. We take the terms up to degree&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:16.000
2 in the Taylor expansion. So, the first two terms&nbsp;
here are just the ones we've already obtained,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:20.080
and we've already simplified that, so why&nbsp;
not just take what we've already got—the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:26.000
formula for the tangent line—and replace&nbsp;
it there? That's what this plus this is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:31.520
so we only need to add this now to it.&nbsp;
That's c + 3dr, and here I'm expanding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:45.720
this out: alpha^2 - 2r alpha + r^2. Now, something&nbsp;
pleasant happens—it's a little bit surprising that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:45.720 --> 00:11:52.320
the thing becomes relatively simple; there's&nbsp;
a lot of cancellation going on here—there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:52.320 --> 00:12:02.680
a little bit of magic trickling through. The&nbsp;
constant term is only a + dr^3; for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:13.320
this minus cr^2 term that was there is going&nbsp;
to be removed when we have an r^2 times c here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:20.320
so those two combine to get rid of that one. The&nbsp;
minus 2dr^3 that we have there, well, that has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:29.320
to be combined with 3dr^3 there for a total of&nbsp;
dr^3. What about the coefficient of alpha? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:29.320 --> 00:12:33.520
here's how many alphas we have to start with, and&nbsp;
then we have to add a certain number of alphas&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:46.480
here. How many? Well, from here, -2cr alpha—that's&nbsp;
exactly canceling this one—and also -6dr^2 times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:57.800
alpha—we already have 3dr^2 times alpha, so we're&nbsp;
going to have -3dr^2 altogether. And finally, the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.800 --> 00:13:06.840
coefficient of alpha^2 is the same as it is here;&nbsp;
we just copy this thing over. This is a polynomial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:15.320
of degree 2—it's called a tangent conic to P at&nbsp;
r. There's a polynomial of degree 1—that's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:25.160
tangent line to P at r; this is the tangent conic&nbsp;
to P at r. And it's all just high school algebra.

00:13:25.160 --> 00:13:29.240
So, I've just copied what we've already&nbsp;
determined here: there's the original&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:29.240 --> 00:13:38.840
polynomial, there's the tangent line to it at&nbsp;
r, there's the tangent conic to it at r. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:38.840 --> 00:13:43.960
for example, if the polynomial happens to be&nbsp;
the one that we drew a picture of earlier,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:52.760
and if we're looking at the point r = 1, then if&nbsp;
you take this expression here, substitute a = 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:52.760 --> 00:14:03.960
b = -3, and so on, and then plug in r = 1, you can&nbsp;
check that you get 7 - 8 alpha—that's a line. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:03.960 --> 00:14:10.640
correspondingly, if you plug the various values&nbsp;
into here, you get 6 - 6 alpha - alpha^2—that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:16.320
a parabola opening downwards. And you&nbsp;
can check if you go back to that previous&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:25.920
picture that these are more or less the line&nbsp;
and the tangent conic that I drew earlier.

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:31.960
Let's make a nice little observation.&nbsp;
We'll observe that if we're looking at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:31.960 --> 00:14:41.520
the tangent line, its slope is just&nbsp;
the derivative of P evaluated at r.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:46.960
That's the same thing that we found for&nbsp;
quadratic polynomials—that the slope of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:53.280
the tangent line is the first derivative&nbsp;
evaluated at the point in question. We see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:53.280 --> 00:14:59.040
here that it's also true for cubics—in&nbsp;
fact, it's true for any polynomial.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:05.560
The other observation is that the coefficient&nbsp;
of alpha^2 in the tangent conic—so,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:11.760
the corresponding top term here—that also has&nbsp;
an interpretation in terms of a sub-derivative:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:11.760 --> 00:15:17.840
that's the second sub-derivative of P&nbsp;
evaluated at r. So, in the formulas for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:17.840 --> 00:15:23.480
the tangent line and the tangent conic,&nbsp;
these terms are already dictated by the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:23.480 --> 00:15:29.440
first and the second derivatives. These&nbsp;
three terms here are perhaps a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:35.360
less predictable but make the&nbsp;
subject sort of interesting.

00:15:35.360 --> 00:15:40.720
So, that finishes our preliminaries having&nbsp;
to do with calculus. Now I just want to say&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:50.440
a few words about a special cubic—the simplest&nbsp;
cubic, P equals alpha^3. There's a graph of it;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:50.440 --> 00:15:57.880
it flattens out around zero, of course, it&nbsp;
increases rather dramatically as you keep going,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:02.200
and it has three important properties that&nbsp;
it's worth pointing out. First of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:10.920
it's an odd function, meaning that if&nbsp;
you evaluate it at -r, you get -P(r). So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:10.920 --> 00:16:19.080
the value at -2, for example, which is -8, is&nbsp;
related to the value at 2 by being negatives—8&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.080 --> 00:16:25.520
and -8 are negatives. That's obvious&nbsp;
because -r^3 is the same as -(r^3).

00:16:27.520 --> 00:16:36.040
The second observation is that P is increasing. If&nbsp;
r1 is less than r2, then when you evaluate P(r1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:44.360
it's less than P(r2). That's perhaps clear if&nbsp;
you just look at the right-hand side first. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:44.360 --> 00:16:49.480
if you have two numbers, r1 and r2,&nbsp;
and r1 is less than r2, well then,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:49.480 --> 00:16:53.720
if you multiply r1 by itself three times,&nbsp;
you're going to get something less than if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:53.720 --> 00:17:01.440
you multiply r2 by itself three times. So, it's&nbsp;
increasing on this side, and then by symmetry,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:09.560
or the odd property, it's also increasing on this&nbsp;
side—in other words, as we go right, it goes up.

00:17:09.560 --> 00:17:16.080
And the third observation is that this&nbsp;
is what's called a one-to-one polynomial.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:16.080 --> 00:17:23.200
What that means is that if the polynomial&nbsp;
values at two points agree—in other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:23.200 --> 00:17:32.080
if P(r1) = P(r2)—then in fact r1 = r2, which&nbsp;
is to say that the function never takes on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:40.360
the same value at different points. So, this&nbsp;
is often referred to in terms of a horizontal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:40.360 --> 00:17:45.680
line—if you have a horizontal line, then it&nbsp;
may or may not meet the graph as it turns out,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:45.680 --> 00:17:51.800
but if it does meet the graph, it only meets&nbsp;
it at one point, right? It's not the case that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:51.800 --> 00:17:58.840
there's a point there and another point there&nbsp;
on the graph—the polynomial is one-to-one.

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:05.400
Okay, so with these preliminaries, here is the&nbsp;
prettiest theorem in calculus as far as I'm&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:11.600
concerned. Let's see if you agree. So, we'll&nbsp;
give this theorem a name: call it the Cubic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:11.600 --> 00:18:18.320
Disjoint Tangent Conic Theorem. It's a rather&nbsp;
long-winded name, but it pretty well tells you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:18.320 --> 00:18:27.000
what the theorem says. It says that the tangent&nbsp;
conics of a cubic polynomial are all distinct,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:35.720
and in more detail, that means there's no point&nbsp;
(x, y) which lies on more than one tangent conic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:35.720 --> 00:18:47.280
so tangent conics never meet. We have a tangent&nbsp;
conic at every point on the curve, so for every&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:52.600
point on the curve, there's a parabola, or&nbsp;
perhaps sometimes a line in a degenerate case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:52.600 --> 00:18:57.120
but typically a parabola opening either&nbsp;
downwards or opening upwards. So, if we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:57.120 --> 00:19:03.000
plot a lot of those quadratic polynomials, the&nbsp;
tangents at a whole number of different points,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:08.000
we're going to find that there's no overlap&nbsp;
whatsoever between any of those quadratics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:15.520
that we've drawn. No matter if we draw&nbsp;
a billion of them, none of them overlap.

00:19:15.520 --> 00:19:22.040
Okay, here's a proof. The proof&nbsp;
is short and sweet. Suppose P is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:31.040
as before, our usual polynomial a + b alpha +&nbsp;
c alpha^2 + d alpha^3 with d not equal to zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:31.040 --> 00:19:36.040
and suppose that we have some point (x, y)&nbsp;
lying on some tangent conic associated with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:43.960
the point r. Well, here is the equation for&nbsp;
the tangent conic, and if (x, y) lies on it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:43.960 --> 00:19:53.120
it means that y = this quantity plus this&nbsp;
quantity times x plus this quantity times x^2.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:53.120 --> 00:19:58.880
This is, after all, the equation of that&nbsp;
tangent conic that we wrote down before,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:58.880 --> 00:20:04.120
so it's all contained in this equation&nbsp;
here. Let's have a good look at it.

00:20:04.120 --> 00:20:08.800
So, what we're going to do is we're going to put&nbsp;
all the terms involving r on that side and all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:08.800 --> 00:20:15.640
the other terms on this side. So, there's&nbsp;
a y, the a comes to the other side as -a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:15.640 --> 00:20:25.800
the bx comes over here, the cx^2 comes over&nbsp;
here, and this term—I'll explain in a minute—on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:31.960
the other side, we have dr^3. In fact, all these&nbsp;
three terms on our left will have a factor of d,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:31.960 --> 00:20:45.240
so we'll pull that out, then we'll have an r^3,&nbsp;
a -3r^2x, a +3rx^2, because we pulled the d out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:45.240 --> 00:20:55.520
front. And at this point, we recognize, or should&nbsp;
recognize, this is almost a binomial expansion of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:55.520 --> 00:21:04.640
(r - x)^3, and to make it such an expansion,&nbsp;
we add -(r - x)^3 inside this bracket. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:04.640 --> 00:21:10.400
we've added -d(x^3) to this side, and&nbsp;
to compensate to keep things equal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:10.400 --> 00:21:21.720
we're going to add -d(x^3) inside here. Well,&nbsp;
then this is just d(r - x)^3. And what's that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:21.720 --> 00:21:30.720
telling us? It's telling us that the value of r&nbsp;
for which the tangent conic passes through (x,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:30.720 --> 00:21:40.080
y) is given by this equation. This is some&nbsp;
number, d is some number which is nonzero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:40.080 --> 00:21:49.680
so something equals (r - x)^3. But we just saw&nbsp;
that the polynomial alpha^3 was one-to-one, so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.680 --> 00:21:58.200
there's at most one r that can possibly have this&nbsp;
property. There's at most one value of r such that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:58.200 --> 00:22:08.240
this thing cubed equals this number divided by d.&nbsp;
That means there's at most one tangent conic that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:08.240 --> 00:22:15.240
goes through the point (x, y)—you can't find two&nbsp;
tangent conics going through (x, y), only one. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:23.880
r is given by this equation, and that determines r&nbsp;
completely. And that's the proof of the theorem—it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:23.880 --> 00:22:29.480
means that through every point, there's at most&nbsp;
one tangent conic going through that point.

00:22:29.480 --> 00:22:34.120
The surprising nature of this result&nbsp;
becomes clearer when we look at an example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:34.120 --> 00:22:40.200
especially when we try to draw some of these&nbsp;
tangent conics. So, here is that cubic that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:49.760
we were looking at before—the one with the&nbsp;
equation 5 - 3 alpha - 4 alpha^2 + alpha^3.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:49.760 --> 00:22:59.200
And here is a formula for the tangent conic&nbsp;
of this thing at r. So, I'm replacing the a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:59.200 --> 00:23:06.520
b, c, and d with 5, -3, -4, and 1, and&nbsp;
that's the formula that we get. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:06.520 --> 00:23:14.480
for various values of r, you can sub in here, and&nbsp;
you're going to get different conics appearing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:14.480 --> 00:23:21.240
and I've graphed some of them at least roughly&nbsp;
here for you. Probably the most interesting and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:21.240 --> 00:23:27.920
most important one is actually the one that&nbsp;
occurs right here at the point 4/3. 4/3 is an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:32.560
important point for this cubic—in fact, it's&nbsp;
the most important point on the cubic—it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:32.560 --> 00:23:40.400
the inflection point. That's exactly the point at&nbsp;
which this second derivative is zero, so at which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:40.400 --> 00:23:46.040
point the tangent conic becomes a degree one&nbsp;
curve instead of being a degree two curve. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:46.040 --> 00:23:52.960
it means that for that particular value of r, this&nbsp;
gives a line, and it's in fact that line there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:52.960 --> 00:24:00.240
in green. So, that's the tangent conic at 4/3, or&nbsp;
the second tangent at 4/3—it's not really a conic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:00.240 --> 00:24:07.720
it's a sort of degenerate conic. This is&nbsp;
sort of a line of inflection of the curve.

00:24:07.720 --> 00:24:17.760
Now, here are some other tangent conics: at&nbsp;
the point 2, the tangent conic looks like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:17.760 --> 00:24:34.920
roughly. At 3, the tangent conic is this one,&nbsp;
roughly. At 4, it's like this. At 5, it should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:34.920 --> 00:24:45.760
be something like that. As we go on further, we&nbsp;
get more and more parabolas in that region there.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:45.760 --> 00:24:53.400
On the other side of the line of inflection,&nbsp;
say at 1, which is just a little bit to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:59.480
left of the inflection point, the tangent conic&nbsp;
there is pretty close to being a line—locally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:59.480 --> 00:25:07.360
it looks like that. Of course, it's part of a&nbsp;
big parabola. Then at zero, the tangent conic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:07.360 --> 00:25:18.480
looks like this—parabola opening downwards.&nbsp;
At -1, it's like this. At -2, it's like this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:26.400
And as we keep on going down, there are more and&nbsp;
more parabolas inside here. So pretty well every&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:26.400 --> 00:25:34.520
point in the plane is approximately on one of&nbsp;
these tangent conics—the tangent conics fill up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:34.520 --> 00:25:42.520
the visible plane, at least approximately. And&nbsp;
if you actually draw a more accurate diagram,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:42.520 --> 00:25:48.720
it's a bit of a marvel to me that all of&nbsp;
these curves can fit together in such a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:48.720 --> 00:25:55.480
beautiful way—they're all tangent to the original&nbsp;
cubic, all exactly tangent at different points,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:55.480 --> 00:26:01.960
but they all miss each other just dramatically,&nbsp;
and they all sort of snuggle together to form&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:02.840 --> 00:26:21.840
kind of a foliation, like a bunch of leaves or&nbsp;
lines that fill up the plane but are curved.

00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:28.080
Alright, so as far as I know, this is a new&nbsp;
theorem. It's a little bit surprising to me&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:28.080 --> 00:26:33.720
that it's new—it's surprising that it's not&nbsp;
well-known, and I very well doubt that it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:33.720 --> 00:26:39.080
really new. It's impossible for me to imagine&nbsp;
that 19th-century mathematicians would not have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:39.080 --> 00:26:44.000
discovered this at some point. But there are&nbsp;
so many works that have been lost in libraries&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:50.240
and in dusty tomes that maybe someday we'll&nbsp;
have access to electronically, but currently,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:50.240 --> 00:26:56.040
they're still essentially buried to us. So, it's&nbsp;
a little bit hard to say for sure that something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:56.040 --> 00:27:04.400
is new, but I think this theorem really&nbsp;
catches one's eye and deserves attention.

00:27:04.400 --> 00:27:12.360
This is just a start to cubic curves, and&nbsp;
I think it's a good place to introduce an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:12.360 --> 00:27:18.720
important new family of objects. We're going to&nbsp;
talk now a little bit about algebraic curves,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:18.720 --> 00:27:24.800
with the idea of extending our&nbsp;
idea of conics and cubics from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:30.200
this polynomial point of view to&nbsp;
a two-variable point of view. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:30.200 --> 00:27:35.120
this is going to allow us to deal with much&nbsp;
more general curves, and the question of how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:35.120 --> 00:27:40.680
does one do calculus with more general curves&nbsp;
is a very interesting one, especially how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:40.680 --> 00:27:47.800
do we do elementary calculus like we've been&nbsp;
doing here? Do the techniques extend? If so,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:47.800 --> 00:27:54.560
how? We're going to make a start on that next time&nbsp;
when we have an introduction to algebraic curves.

00:27:54.560 --> 00:28:08.520
I hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:09.055
[Music]

